{"title_page": "Nick St Aubyn", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name         = Nick St Aubyn\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image        = \n|constituency_MP = [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]]\n|parliament   = \n|majority     = \n|term_start   = 1 May 1997\n|term_end     = 14 May 2001\n|predecessor  = [[David Howell, Baron Howell of Guildford|David Howell]]\n|successor    = [[Sue Doughty]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|11|19|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|restingplace = \n|birthname    = \n|nationality  = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|party        = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = \n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = [[Trinity College, Oxford]]\n|occupation   = \n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|website      = \n}}\n'''Nicholas Francis St Aubyn''' (born 19 November 1955) is a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==Early life==\nSt Aubyn is the younger son of the Hon. Piers St Aubyn [[Military Cross|MC]] by his marriage to Mary Bailey-Southwell, and a grandson of [[Baron St Levan]].<ref name=\"times\" /> He went to [[Eton College]], and [[Trinity College, Oxford]], where he was a member of the [[Oxford University Liberal Club]].<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=157301|title=In the news: Nick St Aubyn|work=Times Higher Education|accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref> He was awarded a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) degree in [[Philosophy, Politics, and Economics|PPE]] in 1977; the BA was later promoted to a [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Master of Arts]] (MA Oxon) degree.<ref name=\"BBC Profile\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/2/28506.stm|title=VOTE 2001 - CANDIDATES|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref>  Before Oxford, he lived and worked in Soweto, South Africa, through a placement with the Project Trust.\n\nHe worked as a Loan Officer for Morgan Guaranty Trust from 1977\u201381.<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> He was the head of the London office of [[JPMorgan Chase|Morgan Futures]] from 1981\u20134, then the head of the [[Pound sterling|Sterling]] and [[Arbitrage]] [[Swaption|Swaps Desk]] from 1984 to 1986.<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> He was Vice President of [[Kleinwort Benson]] Cross Finance from 1986 to 1987.<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> He worked for [[American International Group]]'s Financial Products Division from 1987\u201389. From 1989\u201393, he was Chairman of Gemini Ltd. From 1993\u201397, he was Chairman of Fitzroy Joinery Ltd  in [[Plymouth]].<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /><ref>[http://www.fitzroyjoinery.co.uk Fitzroy Joinery Ltd]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nFrom 1982 to 1986, St Aubyn was a Conservative councillor in [[Westminster City Council]], representing a ward in [[Paddington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmhansrd/vo000310/debtext/00310-14.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 10 Mar 2000 (pt 14)|accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref> He then fought the [[1987 Truro by-election|Truro by-election]] in March 1987  following the death of [[David Penhaligon]],<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> when [[Matthew Taylor (Liberal politician)|Matthew Taylor]] comfortably held the seat for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberals]].  He stood again in [[Truro (UK Parliament constituency)|Truro]] at the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]],<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> more than halving the Liberal majority, but slipped back at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]].<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" />\n\nFollowing the retirement of long-serving Conservative MP and former minister [[David Howell, Baron Howell of Guildford|David Howell]], St Aubyn was selected as Conservative candidate for [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]] in preparation for the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" />  Withstanding the national landslide against his party, he held the seat with a reduced majority over the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], but at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 election]] he narrowly lost the seat to the Liberal Democrat [[Sue Doughty]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/results_constituencies/constituencies/285.stm|title=VOTE 2001 - RESULTS & CONSTITUENCIES - Guildford|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/jonathanisaby/3670311/How_the_Tory_class_of_97_fared_/|title=How the Tory class of '97 fared \u2013 Telegraph Blogs|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=27 October 2010|location=London|date=6 May 2007}}</ref> While in parliament, he served on the [[Education Select Committee]] and was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Michael Portillo]].<ref name=\"times\" /> He did not contest the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 election]], when [[Anne Milton]] narrowly retook the seat for the Conservatives.\n\n==Personal life==\nSt Aubyn married Jane Brooks on 26 April 1980 and they have two sons (Henry and Edward) and three daughters (Kitty, Alice and Camilla).<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" />{{citation needed|reason=No citation for name of wife or children|date=July 2016}} His older brother inherited the title [[Lord St Levan]] from their uncle the [[John St Aubyn, 4th Baron St Levan|4th Baron St Levan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The 4th Lord St Levan|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/naval-obituaries/9977441/The-4th-Lord-St-Levan.html|accessdate=13 May 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n*Nick St Aubyn, ''Custom of the County'' (2010)\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-nick-st-aubyn | Nick St Aubyn }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]]\n | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]\n | before = [[David Howell, Baron Howell of Guildford|David Howell]]\n | after  = [[Sue Doughty]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:St Aubyn, Nick}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:Politics of Guildford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name         = Nick St Aubyn\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image        = \n|constituency_MP = [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]]\n|parliament   = \n|majority     = \n|term_start   = 1 May 1997\n|term_end     = 14 May 2001\n|predecessor  = [[David Howell, Baron Howell of Guildford|David Howell]]\n|successor    = [[Sue Doughty]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|11|19|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|restingplace = \n|birthname    = \n|nationality  = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|party        = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = \n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = [[Trinity College, Oxford]]\n|occupation   = \n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|website      = \n}}\n'''Nicholas Francis St Aubyn''' (born 19 November 1955) is a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==Early life==\nSt Aubyn is the younger son of the Hon. Piers St Aubyn [[Military Cross|MC]] by his marriage to Mary Bailey-Southwell, and a grandson of [[Baron St Levan]].<ref name=\"times\" /> He went to [[Eton College]], and [[Trinity College, Oxford]], where he was a member of the [[Oxford University Liberal Club]].<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=157301|title=In the news: Nick St Aubyn|work=Times Higher Education|accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref> He was awarded a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) degree in [[Philosophy, Politics, and Economics|PPE]] in 1977; the BA was later promoted to a [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Master of Arts]] (MA Oxon) degree.<ref name=\"BBC Profile\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/2/28506.stm|title=VOTE 2001 - CANDIDATES|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref>  Before Oxford, he lived and worked in Soweto, South Africa, through a placement with the Project Trust.\n\nHe worked as a Loan Officer for Morgan Guaranty Trust from 1977-81.<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> He was the head of the London office of [[JPMorgan Chase|Morgan Futures]] from 1981-4, then the head of the [[Pound sterling|Sterling]] and [[Arbitrage]] [[Swaption|Swaps Desk]] from 1984 to 1986.<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> He was Vice President of [[Kleinwort Benson]] Cross Finance from 1986 to 1987.<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> He worked for [[American International Group]]'s Financial Products Division from 1987-89. From 1989-93, he was Chairman of Gemini Ltd. From 1993-97, he was Chairman of Fitzroy Joinery Ltd  in [[Plymouth]].<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /><ref>[http://www.fitzroyjoinery.co.uk Fitzroy Joinery Ltd]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nFrom 1982 to 1986, St Aubyn was a Conservative councillor in [[Westminster City Council]], representing a ward in [[Paddington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmhansrd/vo000310/debtext/00310-14.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 10 Mar 2000 (pt 14)|accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref> He then fought the [[1987 Truro by-election|Truro by-election]] in March 1987  following the death of [[David Penhaligon]],<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> when [[Matthew Taylor (Liberal politician)|Matthew Taylor]] comfortably held the seat for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberals]].  He stood again in [[Truro (UK Parliament constituency)|Truro]] at the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]],<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" /> more than halving the Liberal majority, but slipped back at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]].<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" />\n\nFollowing the retirement of long-serving Conservative MP and former minister [[David Howell, Baron Howell of Guildford|David Howell]], St Aubyn was selected as Conservative candidate for [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]] in preparation for the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" />  Withstanding the national landslide against his party, he held the seat with a reduced majority over the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], but at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 election]] he narrowly lost the seat to the Liberal Democrat [[Sue Doughty]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/results_constituencies/constituencies/285.stm|title=VOTE 2001 - RESULTS & CONSTITUENCIES - Guildford|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/jonathanisaby/3670311/How_the_Tory_class_of_97_fared_/|title=How the Tory class of '97 fared \u2013 Telegraph Blogs|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=27 October 2010|location=London|date=6 May 2007}}</ref> While in parliament, he served on the [[Education Select Committee]] and was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Michael Portillo]].<ref name=\"times\" /> He did not contest the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 election]], when [[Anne Milton]] narrowly retook the seat for the Conservatives.\n\n==Personal life==\nSt Aubyn married Jane Brooks on 26 April 1980 and they have two sons (Henry and Edward) and three daughters (Kitty, Alice and Camilla).<ref name=\"BBC Profile\" />{{citation needed|reason=No citation for name of wife or children|date=July 2016}} His older brother inherited the title [[Lord St Levan]] from their uncle the [[John St Aubyn, 4th Baron St Levan|4th Baron St Levan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The 4th Lord St Levan|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/naval-obituaries/9977441/The-4th-Lord-St-Levan.html|accessdate=13 May 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n*Nick St Aubyn, ''Custom of the County'' (2010)\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-nick-st-aubyn | Nick St Aubyn }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]]\n | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]\n | before = [[David Howell, Baron Howell of Guildford|David Howell]]\n | after  = [[Sue Doughty]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:St Aubyn, Nick}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:Politics of Guildford]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1977-81 \u2192 1977\u201381 (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nick_St_Aubyn"}
{"title_page": "Pierfranco Vianelli", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Pierfranco Vianelli\n| image          = Pierfranco Vianelli.JPG\n| fullname       = Pierfranco Vianelli\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1946|10|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Provaglio d'Iseo]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     =\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| proyears1      =\n| proteam1       =\n| manageyears1   =\n| manageteam1    =\n| majorwins      =\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{ITA}}}}\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[road bicycle racing]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Mexico City]] | [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|Individual road race]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| 1968 Mexico City | [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team time trial|Team time trial]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Pierfranco Vianelli''' (born 20 October 1946) is a former Italian cyclist and Olympic Champion. He won a gold medal at the [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Olympic Games]] in [[Mexico City]], in the [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|Individual Road Race]].<ref name=db-olymp>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=VIANEPIE01 Profile: \"Pierfranco Vianelli\"] &ndash; ''databaseOlympics.com'' (Retrieved on January 4, 2008)</ref> He also won a bronze medal in the [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team time trial|Team Time Trial]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/vi/pierfranco-vianelli-1.html |title=Pierfranco Vianelli Olympic Results |accessdate=17 September 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Sports-reference|vi/pierfranco-vianelli-1.html}}\n* {{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Road Cycling Men}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vianelli, Pierfranco}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Brescia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in cycling]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1940s-stub}}\n{{Italy-cycling-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Pierfranco Vianelli\n| image          = Pierfranco Vianelli.JPG\n| fullname       = Pierfranco Vianelli\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1946|10|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Provaglio d'Iseo]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     =\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| proyears1      =\n| proteam1       =\n| manageyears1   =\n| manageteam1    =\n| majorwins      =\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{ITA}}}}\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[road bicycle racing]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Mexico City]] | [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|Individual road race]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| 1968 Mexico City | [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team time trial|Team time trial]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Pierfranco Vianelli''' (born 20 October 1946) is a former Italian cyclist and Olympic Champion. He won a gold medal at the [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Olympic Games]] in [[Mexico City]], in the [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|Individual Road Race]].<ref name=db-olymp>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=VIANEPIE01 Profile: \"Pierfranco Vianelli\"] &ndash; ''databaseOlympics.com'' (Retrieved on January 4, 2008)</ref> He also won a bronze medal in the [[Cycling at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team time trial|Team Time Trial]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/vi/pierfranco-vianelli-1.html |title=Pierfranco Vianelli Olympic Results |accessdate=17 September 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Sports-reference|vi/pierfranco-vianelli-1.html}}\n* {{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Road Cycling Men}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vianelli, Pierfranco}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Brescia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in cycling]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1940s-stub}}\n{{Italy-cycling-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierfranco_Vianelli"}
{"title_page": "Sir Robert Smith, 3rd Baronet", "text_new": "{{Other people|Robert Smith}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Sir Robert Smith\n| honorific-suffix =[[Baronet|Bt]]\n| image =\n| caption = \n|office       = Chairman of the [[Energy and Climate Change Select Committee]]<br /><small>Interim</small>\n|term_start   = 11 June\n|term_end     = 26 November 2013\n|predecessor  = [[Tim Yeo]]\n|successor    = Tim Yeo\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Aberdeenshire West and Kincardine (UK Parliament constituency)|West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine]] \n| term_start3 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end3 = 30 March 2015\n| parliament3 = \n| majority3 = 3,684 (8.2%)\n| predecessor3 = Constituency created\n| successor3 = [[Stuart Donaldson (Scottish politician)|Stuart Donaldson]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1958|4|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = \n| party = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]\n| relations =\n| children = \n| residence =\n| alma_mater = [[University of Aberdeen]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Sir Robert Hill Smith, 3rd Baronet''' (born 15 April 1958) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[politician]] who was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Aberdeenshire West and Kincardine (UK Parliament constituency)|West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]].\n\n==Early life==\nEducated at the [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylors' School]], [[London]] and the [[University of Aberdeen]] (MA), he was a member of the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] before its merger with the [[The Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] to form the Liberal Democrats.  He served as an [[Aberdeenshire]] Councillor and Convener of the Grampian Joint Police Board 1995\u201397.\n\n[[Sir Robert Workman Smith, 1st Baronet|His grandfather]] represented the same constituency as a [[Unionist Party (Scotland)|Unionist]] from 1924 until 1945.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nSmith contested [[Aberdeen North (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen North]] in 1987 and was first elected to Parliament in 1997. He was the Liberal Democrat Deputy Chief [[Whip (politics)|Whip]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].\n\nSmith's areas of political interest include energy policy, rural issues and international development. He has been a member of the Energy & Climate Change Select Committee since it was created in 2009, acting as Interim Committee Chair from June to November 2013. He sat on the International Development Select Committee from 2007 to 2009.\n\nHe serves as Honorary Vice-President of Energy Action Scotland, a fuel poverty charity, and is a Vice-Chair of the All-Party Group for the UK Offshore Oil and Gas Industry. He is Vice-Chair of the Post Offices APPG and Co-Chairs the APPG on Afghanistan. He represents a large rural constituency where the oil and gas industry, subsea engineering and marine renewables are major employers. He served on the Energy and Climate Change committee from 2009 to 2015.<ref name=\"parl\">{{cite web|title=Sir Robert Smith|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sir-robert-smith/639|website=Parliament UK|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref>\n \nHis previous portfolios include party Energy spokesperson, Deputy Chief Whip and shadowing the Scotland Office; he has served on the Trade & Industry Select Committee, Scottish Affairs Select Committee and the Procedure Committee.<ref name=\"parl\" />\n\nSmith stood for reelection in the 2015 general election, but was defeated by [[Stuart Donaldson (Scottish politician)|Stuart Donaldson]] of the [[Scottish National Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/news/local/snps-stuart-donaldson-wins-west-aberdeenshire-and-kincardine-seat/|title=SNP's Stuart Donaldson wins West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine seat|last=Joseph|first=Anthony|date=8 May 2015|website=Evening Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSmith succeeded to the baronetcy upon his father's death in 1983. He married Fiona Cormack in 1993; they have three daughters.\n\nThe heir presumptive to the title is his brother, Charles Smith.\n\nIn 2013, Smith was diagnosed with [[Parkinson's disease]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-north-east-orkney-shetland-24945303|title=Liberal Democrat MP has Parkinson's|date=14 November 2013|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110629081954/http://www.libdems.org.uk/www.libdems.org.uk/people/robert-smith.html Profile] at the Liberal Democrats\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080821120142/http://scotlibdems.org.uk/people/mps/smith Sir Robert Smith Bt MP] Scottish Liberal Democrats profile\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = robert-smith/639 | hansard = mr-robert-smith | hansardcurr = 746 | guardian = 4875/robert-smith | publicwhip = Robert_Smith | theywork = robert_smith | record = Robert-Smith/West-Aberdeenshire-and-Kincardine/1122 | bbc = 25313.stm | journalisted = }}\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/blood-money-the-mps-cashing-in-on-zimbabwes-misery-856583.html Blood money: the MPs cashing in on Zimbabwe's misery]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine (UK Parliament constituency)|West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine]]\n | years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] \u2013 [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stuart Donaldson (Scottish politician)|Stuart Donaldson]]}}\n{{s-reg|uk-bt}}\n{{s-bef|before=Sir William Gordon Smith, 2nd Baronet}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Smith_baronets#Smith_of_Crowmallie,_Aberdeen_(22_June_1945)|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Crowmallie, Aberdeen)'''|years=1983\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Robert, 3rd Baronet}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Scots]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom|Smith, Robert Hill, 3rd Baronet]]\n[[Category:People educated at Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Democrat councillors]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Democrat MPs]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Robert Smith}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Sir Robert Smith\n| honorific-suffix =[[Baronet|Bt]]\n| image =\n| caption = \n|office       = Chairman of the [[Energy and Climate Change Select Committee]]<br /><small>Interim</small>\n|term_start   = 11 June\n|term_end     = 26 November 2013\n|predecessor  = [[Tim Yeo]]\n|successor    = Tim Yeo\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Aberdeenshire West and Kincardine (UK Parliament constituency)|West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine]] \n| term_start3 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end3 = 30 March 2015\n| parliament3 = \n| majority3 = 3,684 (8.2%)\n| predecessor3 = Constituency created\n| successor3 = [[Stuart Donaldson (Scottish politician)|Stuart Donaldson]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1958|4|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = \n| party = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]\n| relations =\n| children = \n| residence =\n| alma_mater = [[University of Aberdeen]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Sir Robert Hill Smith, 3rd Baronet''' (born 15 April 1958) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[politician]] who was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Aberdeenshire West and Kincardine (UK Parliament constituency)|West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]].\n\n==Early life==\nEducated at the [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylors' School]], [[London]] and the [[University of Aberdeen]] (MA), he was a member of the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] before its merger with the [[The Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] to form the Liberal Democrats.  He served as an [[Aberdeenshire]] Councillor and Convener of the Grampian Joint Police Board 1995-97.\n\n[[Sir Robert Workman Smith, 1st Baronet|His grandfather]] represented the same constituency as a [[Unionist Party (Scotland)|Unionist]] from 1924 until 1945.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nSmith contested [[Aberdeen North (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen North]] in 1987 and was first elected to Parliament in 1997. He was the Liberal Democrat Deputy Chief [[Whip (politics)|Whip]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].\n\nSmith's areas of political interest include energy policy, rural issues and international development. He has been a member of the Energy & Climate Change Select Committee since it was created in 2009, acting as Interim Committee Chair from June to November 2013. He sat on the International Development Select Committee from 2007 to 2009.\n\nHe serves as Honorary Vice-President of Energy Action Scotland, a fuel poverty charity, and is a Vice-Chair of the All-Party Group for the UK Offshore Oil and Gas Industry. He is Vice-Chair of the Post Offices APPG and Co-Chairs the APPG on Afghanistan. He represents a large rural constituency where the oil and gas industry, subsea engineering and marine renewables are major employers. He served on the Energy and Climate Change committee from 2009 to 2015.<ref name=\"parl\">{{cite web|title=Sir Robert Smith|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sir-robert-smith/639|website=Parliament UK|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref>\n \nHis previous portfolios include party Energy spokesperson, Deputy Chief Whip and shadowing the Scotland Office; he has served on the Trade & Industry Select Committee, Scottish Affairs Select Committee and the Procedure Committee.<ref name=\"parl\" />\n\nSmith stood for reelection in the 2015 general election, but was defeated by [[Stuart Donaldson (Scottish politician)|Stuart Donaldson]] of the [[Scottish National Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/news/local/snps-stuart-donaldson-wins-west-aberdeenshire-and-kincardine-seat/|title=SNP's Stuart Donaldson wins West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine seat|last=Joseph|first=Anthony|date=8 May 2015|website=Evening Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSmith succeeded to the baronetcy upon his father's death in 1983. He married Fiona Cormack in 1993; they have three daughters.\n\nThe heir presumptive to the title is his brother, Charles Smith.\n\nIn 2013, Smith was diagnosed with [[Parkinson's disease]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-north-east-orkney-shetland-24945303|title=Liberal Democrat MP has Parkinson's|date=14 November 2013|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110629081954/http://www.libdems.org.uk/www.libdems.org.uk/people/robert-smith.html Profile] at the Liberal Democrats\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080821120142/http://scotlibdems.org.uk/people/mps/smith Sir Robert Smith Bt MP] Scottish Liberal Democrats profile\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = robert-smith/639 | hansard = mr-robert-smith | hansardcurr = 746 | guardian = 4875/robert-smith | publicwhip = Robert_Smith | theywork = robert_smith | record = Robert-Smith/West-Aberdeenshire-and-Kincardine/1122 | bbc = 25313.stm | journalisted = }}\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/blood-money-the-mps-cashing-in-on-zimbabwes-misery-856583.html Blood money: the MPs cashing in on Zimbabwe's misery]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine (UK Parliament constituency)|West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine]]\n | years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] \u2013 [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stuart Donaldson (Scottish politician)|Stuart Donaldson]]}}\n{{s-reg|uk-bt}}\n{{s-bef|before=Sir William Gordon Smith, 2nd Baronet}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Smith_baronets#Smith_of_Crowmallie,_Aberdeen_(22_June_1945)|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Crowmallie, Aberdeen)'''|years=1983\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Robert, 3rd Baronet}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Scots]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom|Smith, Robert Hill, 3rd Baronet]]\n[[Category:People educated at Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Democrat councillors]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Democrat MPs]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\