ategory:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British people of Belgian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]]\n[[Category:British special advisers]]\n[[Category:Children of Holocaust survivors]]\n[[Category:Ed Miliband]]\n[[Category:English atheists]]\n[[Category:English people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Jewish atheists]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n[[Category:Kennedy scholars]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Politicians from London]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. directors and chairmen]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State for the Environment]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chief executive of the International Rescue Committee and former British politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = David Miliband\n|image            = David Miliband 2.jpg\n|office           = [[International Rescue Committee|President of the International Rescue Committee]]\n|term_start       = 1 September 2013\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[George Erik Rupp]]\n|successor        = \n|office2          = [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]]\n|primeminister2   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start2      = 28 June 2007\n|term_end2        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor2     = [[Margaret Beckett]]\n|successor2       = [[William Hague]]\n|office3          = [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start3      = 5 May 2006\n|term_end3        = 27 June 2007\n|predecessor3     = [[Margaret Beckett]]\n|successor3       = [[Hilary Benn]]\n|office4          = [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government|Minister of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n|primeminister4   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start4      = 11 May 2005\n|term_end4        = 5 May 2006\n|predecessor4     = ''Position established''\n|successor4       = [[Ruth Kelly]]\n|office5          = [[Minister for the Cabinet Office|Minister of State for the Cabinet Office]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start5      = 16 December 2004\n|term_end5        = 11 May 2005\n|predecessor5     = [[Ruth Kelly]]\n|successor5       = [[Liam Byrne]]\n|office6          = [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Schools]]\n|primeminister6   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start6      = 24 October 2002\n|term_end6        = 16 December 2004\n|predecessor6     = [[Stephen Timms]]\n|successor6       = [[Stephen Twigg]]\n|office7          = Director of the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]]\n|term_start7      = 1 May 1997\n|term_end7        = 7 June 2001\n|primeminister7   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|predecessor7     = [[Norman Blackwell]]\n|successor7       = [[Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis|Andrew Adonis]]\n|office8          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Shields (UK Parliament constituency)|South Shields]]\n|term_start8      = 7 June 2001\n|term_end8        = 15 April 2013\n|predecessor8     = [[David Clark, Baron Clark of Windermere|David Clark]]\n|successor8       = [[Emma Lewell-Buck]]\n|birth_name       = David Wright Miliband\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1965|7|15|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[London]], England, UK\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|spouse           = {{marriage|Louise Shackelton|1998}}\n|children         = Isaac Miliband & Jacob Miliband\n|parents           = [[Ralph Miliband]]<br />[[Marion Kozak]]\n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|alma_mater       = {{nowrap|[[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]}}<br />[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n}}\n'''David Wright Miliband''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}} (born 15 July 1965) is a British public policy analyst who is the [[President (corporate title)|president]] and [[Chief executive officer|chief executive officer]] (CEO) of the [[International Rescue Committee]]. A former British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician,<ref name=\":1\" /> who was the [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]] from 2007 to 2010<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.some.ox.ac.uk/research/global-ocean-commission/the-commissioners/david-miliband/|title=David Miliband \u2014 Somerville College Oxford|publisher=University of Oxford|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref> and the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Shields (UK Parliament constituency)|South Shields]] from [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] to [[2013 South Shields by-election|2013]], he and his brother, [[Ed Miliband]], were the first siblings to sit in the [[UK Cabinet|Cabinet]] simultaneously since [[Edward Stanley, Lord Stanley (died 1938)|Lord Edward Stanley]] and [[Oliver Stanley]]<nowiki/> in 1938.\n\nHe started his career at the [[Institute for Public Policy Research]]. Aged 29, he became [[Tony Blair]]'s Head of Policy while the Labour Party was in opposition, and he was a contributor to Labour's manifesto for the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 election]], which brought the party to power. Blair subsequently made him head of the [[Number 10 Policy Unit|Prime Minister's Policy Unit]] from 1997 to 2001, at which point Miliband was elected to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] for the seat of [[South Shields (UK Parliament constituency)|South Shields]].\n\nMiliband spent the next few years in various junior ministerial posts, including at the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]], before joining the [[Cabinet (UK)|Cabinet]] in 2006 as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]]. His tenure in this post saw [[Global warming|climate change]] consolidated as a priority for policymakers. On the succession of [[Gordon Brown]] as [[Prime Minister of the UK|Prime Minister]] in 2007, Miliband was promoted to become [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rescue.org/david-miliband|title=David Miliband \u2013 President & CEO of the International Rescue Committee (IRC)|publisher=rescue.org|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref> At the age of 41, he became the youngest person to hold that office since [[David Owen]] 30 years earlier. In September 2010, Miliband narrowly lost the [[2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|Labour leadership election]] to his brother Ed. On 29 September 2010, he announced that to avoid \"constant comparison\" with his brother Ed, and because of the \"perpetual, distracting and destructive attempts to find division where there is none, and splits where they don't exist, all to the detriment of the party's cause\", he would not stand for the [[Official Opposition Shadow Cabinet (United Kingdom)|Shadow Cabinet]].<ref name=\"Mulholland-29-09-2010\">{{cite news|last=Mulholland |first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/sep/29/david-miliband-quits-frontline-politics |accessdate=29 September 2010 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 September 2010 |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2010/sep/29/david-miliband-quits-frontline-politics |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=live |title=David Miliband quits frontline politics |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April 2013, Miliband [[Resignation from the British House of Commons|resigned from Parliament]] in order to take up the posts of President and CEO of the International Rescue Committee in New York City, which triggered a [[2013 South Shields by-election|by-election]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=BBC21947497/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.shieldsgazette.com/news/local-news/may-2-the-likely-date-for-south-shields-by-election-1-5537327 |title=May 2 the likely date for South Shields by-election |newspaper=[[Shields Gazette]] |date=28 March 2013 |accessdate=29 September 2013 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.shieldsgazette.com/news/local-news/may-2-the-likely-date-for-south-shields-by-election-1-5537327 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\n===Early life and family===\nBorn in London, Miliband is the eldest son of immigrant parents, [[Belgium|Belgian]]-born [[Marxism|Marxist]] sociologist [[Ralph Miliband]] and Polish-born [[Marion Kozak]], both from Polish [[Jews|Jewish]] families.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Corner Office: The Devil Can't Have the Best Tunes|last=Gelles|first=David|date=April 21, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=ref111>\"Being Jewish must have an influence on the way I think. I am the child of Jewish immigrants and that is a very important part of my identity.\" \u2013 from {{cite news|url=http://www.thejc.com/articles/david-miliband-red-green-a-generation |last=Josephs |first=Bernard |title=David Miliband: Red to green in a generation |work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] |date=22 December 2006 |accessdate=30 November 2009 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.thejc.com/articles/david-miliband-red-green-a-generation |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mendick |first=Robert |location=London |date=16 May 2010 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/family/7730052/The-miraculous-escape-of-Marion-Miliband.html |title=The miraculous escape of Marion Miliband |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=7 June 2010 |archivedate=23 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523020101/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/family/7730052/The-miraculous-escape-of-Marion-Miliband.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> The latter was a teacher before she became a [[Homemaking|homemaker]]. He was given the middle name of \"Wright\" after the American sociologist [[C. Wright Mills]], a friend of his father.<ref>{{cite news|last=Birnbaum |first=Norman |url=http://www.thenation.com/article/half-forgotten-prophet-c-wright-mills |title=The half forgotten prophet: C. Wright Mills |work=[[The Nation]] |date=30 March 2009 |accessdate=30 January 2014 |archivedate=23 March 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323220937/http://www.thenation.com/article/half-forgotten-prophet-c-wright-mills |df=dmy }}</ref> He has said \"I am the child of Jewish immigrants and that is a very important part of my identity.\"<ref name=ref111/> Both his [[History of the Jews in Poland|Polish Jewish]] paternal grandparents lived in the [[Warsaw Ghetto|Jewish quarter of Warsaw]]. His paternal grandfather, Samuel, a trained leather worker, served in the [[Red Army]] in the [[Polish\u2013Soviet War]] of 1919\u20131921 before moving to Belgium.<ref>{{cite news|author=Luke Harding |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/may/30/russia |title=Luke Harding: Moscow diary |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=16 March 2010 |location=London |date=30 May 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531095234/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2008/may/30/russia |archivedate=31 May 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Porter |first=Andrew |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/andrewporter/5186517/David_Miliband_fourletter_abuse_from_Russian_foreign_minister/ |title=David Miliband four-letter abuse from Russian foreign minister |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=9 September 2008 |accessdate=16 March 2010 |publisher=Telegraph Blogs |location=London |url-status=live |archivedate=16 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216183958/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/andrewporter/5186517/David_Miliband_fourletter_abuse_from_Russian_foreign_minister/ |df=dmy }}</ref> His paternal grandmother, Renia (later known as Ren\u00e9e), also moved to Belgium, where she first met Sam, and the couple married in 1923.<ref>M. Newman, ''ibid'', p. 5</ref> The [[Battle of France|German invasion of Belgium]] in May 1940 split the Miliband family in half: Ralph and father Samuel fled to England,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/feb/28/schools.labour |title=In the house of the rising sons |author=Andy Beckett |newspaper=The Guardian |date=28 February 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202130017/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2004/feb/28/schools.labour |archivedate=2 February 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> while Ralph's mother Ren\u00e9e and baby sister Nan stayed behind for the duration of the war. They were not reunited until 1950.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lipman-miliband.org.uk/biographies.html |publisher=The Lipman-Miliband Trust |date=15 August 2007 |title=Biographies: Lipman, Miliband & Saville |accessdate=22 October 2007 |archivedate=31 October 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071031102246/http://www.lipman-miliband.org.uk/biographies.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> His mother, a human rights campaigner and early [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament|CND]] member, survived [[the Holocaust]] thanks to being [[Rescue of Jews by Poles during the Holocaust|protected]] by Catholic Poles but her father, David's maternal grandfather did not.<ref name=\":1\" /> During his visit to Poland in June 2009, Miliband went to his family tomb in the [[Jewish cemeteries of Warsaw|Jewish Cemetery in Warsaw]]. He said of Poland, \"My mother was born here, her life was saved by those who risked theirs sheltering her from Nazi oppression\", and that he is \"one of the million [[Poles in the United Kingdom|Britons who have Polish blood\"]].<ref name=tch>{{cite news|author=Kamil Tchorek|title=David Miliband visits family grave in Poland|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article6564505.ece |work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=28 June 2009|location=London|date=24 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=23 June 2009 |url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/news/latest-news/?view=Speech&id=19993154 |publisher=[[Foreign & Commonwealth Office]] |title=European renewal amidst global adversity (23/06/2009) |accessdate=28 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927033946/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/news/latest-news/?view=Speech&id=19993154 |archivedate=27 September 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Education===\n[[File:David Miliband, Davos 2010.jpg|thumb|Miliband during the [[World Economic Forum|WEF]] 2010]]\nMiliband was educated at [[Primrose Hill]] Primary School, in [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9578145/Im-sorry-to-say-it-but-my-old-school-chum-isnt-PM-material.html|title=I 'm sorry to say it, but my old school chum isn't PM material.|last=Johnson|first=Boris|date=2012|work=The Telegraph|access-date=25 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Horsforth|Newlaithes Primary School]], in [[Leeds]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/archive/2010/06/24/Otley+%26+Aireborough+News+%28news_otleyaire%29/8237015.Miliband_says_school_taught_him_a_lot______/ |last=McIntyre |first=Annette |newspaper=Telegraph & Argus |title=...and that he would never be a professional footballer |date=24 June 2010 |accessdate=10 January 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/archive/2010/06/24/Otley+%26+Aireborough+News+%28news_otleyaire%29/8237015.Miliband_says_school_taught_him_a_lot______/ |archivedate=30 June 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> In September 1976, he passed the entrance examination to the newly independent, fee-paying [[Bradford Grammar School]] and from 1978-83, attended [[Haverstock School|Haverstock Comprehensive School]] in [[North London]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://education.guardian.co.uk/schools/story/0,,727020,00.html |newspaper=The Guardian |title=Meet the new boy |date=4 June 2002 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://education.guardian.co.uk/schools/story/0%2C%2C727020%2C00.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> He obtained four [[GCE Advanced Level|A-level]]s (grades BBBD),<ref>{{cite news|last=Pierce |first=Andrew |location=London |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/2475236/Profile-of-Foreign-Secretary-David-Miliband.html |title=Profile of Foreign Secretary David Miliband |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=30 July 2008 |accessdate=7 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/2475236/Profile-of-Foreign-Secretary-David-Miliband.html |archivedate=30 June 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> and won admission to the University of Oxford. He studied at [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]], and obtained a [[first-class honours]] degree in [[Philosophy, politics and economics|Philosophy, Politics and Economics]].<ref>{{cite news|date=17 August 2003 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/breakfast_with_frost/3158091.stm |title=A Levels discussed |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=2 May 2007 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/breakfast_with_frost/3158091.stm |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> From 1988-89, he received a master's degree in [[Political Science]] at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where he was a [[Kennedy Scholarship|Kennedy Scholar]].<ref name=biog>{{cite web |accessdate=22 September 2008 |url=http://www.davidmiliband.info/biography.htm |title=David Miliband Biography |archivedate=30 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.davidmiliband.info/biography.htm |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Political biography==\nMiliband's first job was as a [[Political science|political analyst]] at the [[National Council for Voluntary Organisations]] (NCVO). From 1989 to 1994, he worked as a Research Fellow and [[policy analysis|policy analyst]] at the [[Institute for Public Policy Research]] (IPPR). He was appointed Secretary of the IPPR's Commission on Social Justice upon its foundation in 1992 by the then leader of the Labour Party, [[John Smith (Labour Party leader)|John Smith]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Commission on Social Justice |url=http://www.ippr.org/ipprcommissions/index.asp?id=2378 |publisher=[[Institute for Public Policy Research|IPPR]] |accessdate=3 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.ippr.org/ipprcommissions/index.asp?id=2378 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Policy adviser to Tony Blair (1994\u20132001)===\nIn 1994 Miliband became [[Tony Blair]]'s Head of Policy and was a contributor to [[List of Labour Party (UK) general election manifestos|Labour's manifesto]] for the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. After Labour's victory in that election, Blair made him the de facto head of the [[Number 10 Policy Unit|Prime Minister's Policy Unit]], a position which he held until the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 election]]. He was given the nickname \"[[Brains (Thunderbirds)|Brains]]\" by [[Alastair Campbell]], after the ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'' character.<ref name=\"Heir to Blair?\">{{cite news |date=20 October 2002 |authorlink=Andrew Rawnsley |title=Heir to Blair? |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/comment/story/0,,815389,00.html |work=[[The Observer]] |accessdate=3 May 2007 |location=London |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://observer.guardian.co.uk/comment/story/0%2C%2C815389%2C00.html |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Member of Parliament===\nIn the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]] he was elected to Parliament for the Labour stronghold of [[South Shields (UK Parliament constituency)|South Shields]], succeeding [[David Clark, Baron Clark of Windermere|David Clark]]. After a year as a [[backbench]] MP he was appointed Schools Minister, a [[Minister (government)|junior minister]] in the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]] in June 2002.\n\nIn 2003, Miliband voted to go to war in Iraq.  Later, in 2010, he said that his decision was based on his belief that Iraq then had weapons of mass destruction.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sparrow |first=Andrew |title=Miliband challenged over ministers' explanations for Iraq war decision |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/mar/08/david-miliband-iraq-war-inquiry |date=8 March 2010 |archivedate=4 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104144307/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/mar/08/david-miliband-iraq-war-inquiry |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 15 December 2004, in the reshuffle following the resignation of [[David Blunkett]], he replaced [[Ruth Kelly]] as a [[Minister for the Cabinet Office|Cabinet Office Minister]].\n\nFollowing Labour's third consecutive [[2005 United Kingdom general election|election victory in May 2005]], he was promoted to the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] as [[Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government|Minister of State for Communities and Local Government]] within the [[Office of the Deputy Prime Minister]]. This was a newly created cabinet-level post with responsibility for housing, planning, regeneration and local government. Because the [[Deputy Prime Minister]], [[John Prescott]], was the [[Departments of the Government of the United Kingdom|Departmental Minister]] officially in charge of these portfolios, Miliband was not given the title Secretary of State but he was appointed a [[Privy council|Privy Councillor]] and became a full member of the Cabinet.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=12 September 2008 |url=http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/Page76.asp#m |title=Privy Council Members |archivedate=24 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081224234444/http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/Page76.asp#m |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Environment Secretary (2006\u20132007)===\nOn 5 May 2006 following the [[2006 United Kingdom local elections|local elections]] [[Tony Blair]] made a major [[cabinet reshuffle]] in which Miliband replaced [[Margaret Beckett]] as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].<ref>{{cite news|date=5 May 2006 |title=Reshuffle seeks to rejuvenate |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4976428.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=2 May 2007 |first=Nick |last=Assinder |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4976428.stm |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> Miliband has said he believes agriculture is important for the UK's cultural heritage, economy and society and also for the environment. He has said disease control should be balanced with [[animal welfare]]. He attaches importance to reaching a \"fair balance\" among consumers, farmers, manufacturers and retailers. Miliband also believes the [[European Union]] and the [[World Trade Organization]] affect power relations between British and foreign farmers.<ref>{{cite web|date=4 July 2006 |title=Speech by the Rt Hon. David Miliband MP \u2013 \"One planet farming\" at the Royal Agricultural Show, Monday 3 July 2006 |accessdate=2 May 2007 |url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/corporate/ministers/speeches/david-miliband/dm060703.htm |publisher=[[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|DEFRA]] |archivedate=6 June 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070606214910/http://www.defra.gov.uk/corporate/ministers/speeches/david-miliband/dm060703.htm |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nHe was the first British cabinet member to have a blog, though claims of excessive cost to the taxpayer provoked some controversy.<ref>{{cite news|date=16 June 2006 |title=\u00a340,000 \u2013 the real cost of reading David's diary |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/pandora/16340000--the-real-cost-of-reading-davids-diary-404208.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |first=Henry |last=Deedes |accessdate=27 July 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421232803/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/pandora/16340000--the-real-cost-of-reading-davids-diary-404208.html |archivedate=21 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=11 September 2006 |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm060616/text/60616w1003.htm#06061625000057 |work=Hansard |date=16 June 2006 |title=Written Parliamentary Question on cost of blog |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825210534/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm060616/text/60616w1003.htm#06061625000057 |url-status=live |archivedate=25 August 2006 |df=dmy }}</ref> In January 2007 Miliband sparked minor controversy by saying there was no evidence [[organic food]] was better than [[conventionally grown]] produce, though he later clarified that he was referring specifically to health benefits.<ref>{{cite web|date=7 January 2007 |title=Miliband questions organic quality |accessdate=2 May 2007 |url=http://www.epolitix.com/EN/News/200701/0a0b11d2-2dbf-43a8-9fa2-5e497e617142.htm |publisher=ePolitix.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070619102641/http://www.epolitix.com/EN/News/200701/0a0b11d2-2dbf-43a8-9fa2-5e497e617142.htm |archivedate=19 June 2007 |url-status=live |df=dmy }} See also: {{cite web|date=8 January 2007 |title=Making the Most of Organic Food |publisher=DEFRA |accessdate=2 May 2007 |url=http://www.davidmiliband.defra.gov.uk/blogs/ministerial_blog/archive/2007/01/08/4320.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609093932/http://www.davidmiliband.defra.gov.uk/blogs/ministerial_blog/archive/2007/01/08/4320.aspx |archivedate=9 June 2007 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nMiliband is an advocate for international awareness of [[Global warming|climate change]] and believes the cooperation of all nations is needed for environmental reform. Miliband's focuses include food retail waste management and [[greenhouse gas]] emissions in agricultural industries. He believes that the EU should go further in two areas: a low carbon global economy and global action on climate change. He also wants Europe to increase its economic competitiveness. By switching over to a low carbon economy, he plans to tackle climate change. He hopes to ensure a stable price on energy by securing an energy source and announced the Government's plans to legislate for carbon reductions at the [[United Nations General Assembly]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=DEFRA |url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/corporate/ministers/speeches/david-miliband/dm070606.htm |first=David |last=Miliband |title=Greening the American Dream |date=6 June 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609230056/http://www.defra.gov.uk/corporate/ministers/speeches/david-miliband/dm070606.htm |url-status=live |archivedate=9 June 2007 |df=dmy }} See also: {{UN document|docid=A-62-PV.9|body=General Assembly|type=Verbatim Report|session=62|meeting=9|page=45|anchor=pg045-bk02-pa21|date=27 September 2007|speakername=Mr. Miliband|speakernation=United Kingdom|accessdate=12 November 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2006, in an effort to put environmental reform into action, Miliband developed a place for a collaborative \"environmental contract\" to be developed on a [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Defra]] Wiki site. It was subsequently linked to by blogger [[Paul Staines]], and mocked, after which further edits by guest users were temporarily prevented.<ref>{{cite web|date=1 November 2006|title=Wiki Wickedness |url=http://5thnovember.blogspot.com/2006/09/wiki-wickedness.html|publisher=Global & General Nominees LLC|accessdate=1 September 2006}}</ref> Miliband's emphasis on the necessity of an entirely cooperative effort to effectively instigate a low carbon lifestyle worldwide has led him to advocate an open dialogue among citizens about environmental issues through web-based blogging.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.defra.gov.uk/|title=Defra website}}</ref> Whilst Environment Secretary, Miliband called for all 27 nations of the [[European Union]] to unify in backing proposals to cut harmful emissions by 30% by 2020.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC News |date=18 February 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/6369171.stm |title='Now or never' for climate action |accessdate=2 January 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520041929/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/6369171.stm |archivedate=20 May 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nMiliband has floated the idea of every citizen being issued with a \"Carbon Credit Card\" to improve personal carbon thrift. Miliband argues individuals have to be empowered to tackle [[global warming]] \u2014 \"the mass mobilising movement of our age\".<ref>{{cite news|date=11 December 2006 |title=Carbon 'credit card' considered |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6167671.stm |accessdate=2 May 2007 |publisher=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070119080831/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6167671.stm |archivedate=19 January 2007 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Foreign Secretary (2007\u20132010)===\n[[File:Miliband Clinton.jpg|thumb|Miliband with U.S. Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]], February 2009]]\nOn 28 June 2007, the day after [[Gordon Brown]] became Prime Minister, Miliband was appointed [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]]. He was Britain's third youngest Foreign Secretary and the youngest person to be appointed to the post since [[David Owen]] (in office 21 February 1977 \u2013 4 May 1979). [[Anthony Eden]] had assumed office at the age of 37 in 1935. David's younger brother, the economist [[Ed Miliband]], was the [[Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]], making them the first siblings to serve together in [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] since [[Edward Stanley, Lord Stanley (died 1938)|Edward, Lord Stanley]], and his brother [[Oliver Stanley|Oliver]] in 1938.\n\nMiliband's first [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] questions session as Foreign Secretary in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] was on 3 July 2007.<ref>{{cite web|author=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons, Westminster |url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070703/debtext/70703-0002.htm |title=tso.co.uk |publisher=Parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk |accessdate=16 March 2010 |archivedate=25 August 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825210534/http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070703/debtext/70703-0002.htm |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\nOn the morning of 13 December 2007, Miliband stood in for Prime Minister, [[Gordon Brown]] at the official signing ceremony in [[Lisbon]] of the [[Treaty of Lisbon|EU Reform Treaty]], which was attended by all other European heads of government. Brown was otherwise engaged at the House of Commons, appearing before the [[Liaison Committee]], and travelled to Portugal to sign the treaty in the afternoon.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/eu/story/0,,2227505,00.html |title=Miliband plays stand-in at lavish EU relaunch |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |first=Ian |last=Traynor |date=14 December 2007 |accessdate=1 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215221710/http://politics.guardian.co.uk/eu/story/0%2C%2C2227505%2C00.html |archivedate=15 December 2007 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> He was left on his own again by the Prime Minister to speak in favour of the [[European Union (Amendment) Act 2008|European Union (Amendment) Bill]] in the House on 21 January 2008.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200708/cmhansrd/cm080121/debindx/80121-x.htm Hansard: Volume No. 470 Part No. 34 House of Commons Debates January 21, 2008] and see [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200708/cmhansrd/cm080121/debtext/80121-0022.htm Division #50].</ref>\n\nOn 21 February 2008, Miliband admitted (despite previous government denials) that two U.S. [[extraordinary rendition]] flights had stopped on [[Diego Garcia]], a U.K. territory, in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|date=21 February 2008 |accessdate=21 February 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7256587.stm |title=UK apology on US terror flights |publisher=BBC News |archivedate=25 August 2006 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825210534/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7256587.stm |df=dmy }}</ref> When questioned as to whether the government had deliberately misled the public over rendition, Miliband apologised and stated that the government had \"made a mistake\".\n\nOn 5 February 2009, Miliband made a statement to the House of Commons concerning [[Guant\u00e1namo Bay |Guantanamo Bay]] detainee and former British resident [[Binyam Mohamed|Benyam Mohammed]].<ref>{{cite web|date=5 February 2009 |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2009-02-05a.989.0 |title=Miliband statement on Benyam Mohammed |publisher=[[TheyWorkForYou]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217151956/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2009-02-05a.989.0 |archivedate=17 February 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> A week later Mohamed's American lawyer Yvonne Bradley flew to Britain to urge the Foreign Office to press harder for his release. On 23 February 2009, Benyam Mohammed returned to Britain and was granted temporary residence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/7906684.stm |title=Freed detainee 'happy to be home' |publisher=BBC News |date=23 February 2009 |accessdate=26 December 2009 |archivedate=23 February 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223214936/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/7906684.stm |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7906880.stm |title=Military lawyer who freed Mohamed |publisher=BBC News |date=24 February 2009 |accessdate=26 December 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227103654/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7906880.stm |archivedate=27 February 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> However, in July 2010, Clive Stafford Smith accused former Foreign Secretary David Miliband of \"fighting tooth and nail\" to prevent the release of vital documents during the Binyam Mohamed case.\n\n====India trip====\nAfter his trip to India in 2008 following the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Mumbai attacks]], Miliband wrote in an article that \"resolution of the dispute over [[Kashmir conflict|Kashmir]] would help deny extremists in the region one of their main calls to arms, and allow Pakistani authorities to focus more effectively on tackling the threat on their western borders\".<ref>{{cite news|title=David Miliband: 'War on terror' was wrong |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/jan/15/david-miliband-war-terror |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=15 April 2010 |location=London |date=15 January 2009 |archivedate=17 January 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090117013607/http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2009/jan/15/david-miliband-war-terror |df=dmy }}</ref> This sparked an angry response from the [[Government of India|Indian government]], whose long standing policy had been not to accept any third party involvement in the [[Kashmir conflict|dispute of Kashmir]]. An Indian analyst suggested that his tone implied that India must shoulder some of the responsibility because of its policies in Kashmir.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kapil Komireddi |date=23 January 2009 |accessdate=16 March 2010 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/jan/23/india-kashmir |title=Keep out of Kashmir |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125144011/http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2009/jan/23/india-kashmir |archivedate=25 January 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> Some reports also said that Miliband's tone towards the Indian Prime Minister and the Finance Minister had been aggressive, and that he had been excused for being a \"young man\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/milibands-trip-to-india-a-disaster-after-kashmir-gaffe-1418914.html |title=Miliband's trip to India 'a disaster', after Kashmir gaffe |newspaper=The Independent |date=18 January 2009 |accessdate=16 March 2010 |location=London |first=Jane |last=Merrick |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100423202422/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/milibands-trip-to-india-a-disaster-after-kashmir-gaffe-1418914.html |archivedate=23 April 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/4283097/David-Miliband-comments-on-Kashmir-welcomed-by-terrorist-group.html |title=David Miliband comments on Kashmir welcomed by 'terrorist' group |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=18 January 2009 |archivedate=25 August 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825210534/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/4283097/David-Miliband-comments-on-Kashmir-welcomed-by-terrorist-group.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n====Sri Lanka ceasefire====\nDuring the latter stages of the [[Sri Lanka Army|Sri Lankan Army]]'s [[2008\u20132009 Sri Lankan Army Northern offensive|2008/09 offensive]] against the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|LTTE]], Miliband travelled to Sri Lanka to press the [[Government of Sri Lanka|government]] to call a ceasefire with the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|Tamil Tigers]], citing concerns for civilians caught in the crossfire.<ref>{{cite news\n |first=Jeremy \n |last=Page \n |work=[[The Times]] \n |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6174544.ece \n |title=David Miliband heads to Sri Lanka to urge ceasefire \n |location=London \n |date=26 April 2009 \n |accessdate=1 April 2010 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509081240/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6174544.ece \n |archivedate=9 May 2009 \n |url-status=live \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> Miliband's visit was met with protests by Sri Lankan nationalists, who accused Miliband of attempting to save the lives of Tamil Tiger militants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/Asia/Story/STIStory_370219.html |title=Monks protest Miliband visit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130202735/http://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/Asia/Story/STIStory_370219.html |archivedate=30 November 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> During the [[End of the Sri Lankan Civil War|victory]] celebrations that took place a few weeks later, a burning effigy of Miliband was reported to have been tossed over the gate of the British [[High commissioner|High Commission]] in [[Colombo]].<ref>{{cite news|location=London |work=The Times |url=https://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6310422.ece |title=Effigy of David Miliband burnt on streets of Sri Lankan capital |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519190922/https://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6310422.ece |url-status=live |archivedate=19 May 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010 articles published in the British newspapers ''The Guardian'' and ''The Daily Telegraph'' highlighted that Miliband was spending two-thirds of his time focusing on the Sri Lankan civil war, largely due to domestic political calculations. The source of the articles was a leaked US diplomatic cable published by [[WikiLeaks|Wiki Leaks]]. The articles quoted Tim Waite, a Foreign Office official as saying <blockquote>that much of [Her Majesty's government] and ministerial attention to Sri Lanka is due to the \"very vocal\" Tamil diaspora in the UK, numbering over 300,000, who had been protesting in front of Parliament since 6 April.</blockquote> According to Wikileaks, this was reported by Richard Mills a United States Embassy worker in UK.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2 December 2010 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/wikileaks/8175415/WikiLeaks-David-Miliband-championed-aid-to-Sri-Lanka-to-win-votes-of-Tamils-in-UK.html |title=WikiLeaks: David Miliband 'championed aid to Sri Lanka to win votes of Tamils in UK' |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205034538/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/wikileaks/8175415/WikiLeaks-David-Miliband-championed-aid-to-Sri-Lanka-to-win-votes-of-Tamils-in-UK.html |archivedate=5 December 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/dec/01/wikileaks-david-miliband-sri-lanka |title=Wikileaks cables: David Miliband focused on Sri Lankan war 'to win votes' |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203182316/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/dec/01/wikileaks-david-miliband-sri-lanka |archivedate=3 December 2010 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nRichard Mills further wrote on his cable, saying that<blockquote>with UK elections on the horizon and many Tamils living in Labour constituencies with slim majorities, the government is paying particular attention to Sri Lanka, with Miliband recently remarking to Waite that he was spending 60 per cent of his time at the moment on Sri Lanka.</blockquote>\n\n====Comments over terrorism====\nIn August 2009, Miliband was a guest on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Great Lives]]'' programme, choosing [[South African Communist Party]] leader and anti-[[apartheid]] activist [[Joe Slovo]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=16 March 2010 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00lyfm8 |title=Radio 4 Programmes \u2013 Great Lives, Series 19, Joe Slovo |work=[[BBC Radio 4]] |publisher=BBC News |archivedate=15 August 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815191947/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00lyfm8 |df=dmy }}</ref> Miliband stated during the programme, in a response to a question about terrorism, that \"yes, there are circumstances in which it is justifiable and yes, there are circumstances in which it is effective, but it is never effective on its own\". These comments were criticised by [[Menzies Campbell]] and [[William Hague]].<ref>{{cite news|author=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Mulholland and agencies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/aug/17/miliband-terrorism-menzies-campbell |title=Miliband attacked over terrorism comments |newspaper=The Guardian |date=17 August 2009 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817212247/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2009/aug/17/miliband-terrorism-menzies-campbell |archivedate=17 August 2009 |accessdate=16 March 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n====European Foreign Minister====\nThe [[Treaty of Lisbon]] creates the post of [[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy|High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy]] for the [[European Union]], a post commonly known as the European Foreign Minister. In autumn 2009, as the treaty came close to coming into force, Miliband was named as being under consideration for the post as EU officials regarded him as \"ideal material\".<ref name=\"EU Foreign Minister\">{{cite news|work=[[The Sunday Telegraph]] |publisher=[[HighBeam Research]] |author1=Patrick Hennessy |author2=Bruno Waterfield |title=... or it could be Miliband, the EU international overlord |url=http://www.highbeam.com/Search?searchTerm=...+or+it+could+be+Miliband+the+EU+international+overlord&searchType=Article&currentPage=0&orderBy= |date=11 October 2009 |page=8 |archivedate=20 November 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091120051755/http://www.highbeam.com/Search?searchTerm=...+or+it+could+be+Miliband+the+EU+international+overlord&searchType=Article&currentPage=0&orderBy= |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Miliband publicly insisted that he was not available to fill the post, as he was committed to remaining in the British cabinet.<ref name=\"Not available\">{{cite news|work=[[The Independent]]|first=Nigel|last=Morris|title=Miliband 'will stay in government'|date=2 November 2009|page=8}}{{Verify source|date=July 2014}}</ref> [[Catherine Ashton|Baroness Ashton]], a fellow British Labour politician and then [[European Commissioner for Trade]], was ultimately appointed to the post instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8369477.stm |title=Baroness Ashton appointed as EU's foreign policy chief |date=19 November 2009 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=25 November 2009 |archivedate=20 November 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091120051755/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8369477.stm |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n====Relations with Israel====\nOn 23 March 2010, the UK expelled an Israeli diplomat owing to claims that an embassy official from that country forged passports, relating to the [[assassination of Mahmoud Al-Mabhouh]], and Miliband gave a public warning against travel to Israel because of identity theft concerns.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/uk-expels-israeli-diplomat-over-dubai-case/ |title=UK expels Israeli diplomat over Dubai case |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=David |last=Stringer |date=23 March 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140405014116/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/uk-expels-israeli-diplomat-over-dubai-case/ |archivedate=5 April 2014 |url-status=live |accessdate=26 March 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==2010 Labour leadership election==\n{{Main|2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)}}\n\n===Background===\nOn 29 July 2008, Miliband wrote an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'' that outlined his vision of a future of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] but made no mention of [[Gordon Brown]].<ref>{{cite news|first=David |last=Miliband |date=29 July 2008 |title=Against all odds we can still win, on a platform for change |accessdate=2 August 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/jul/29/davidmiliband.labour |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080731005830/http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2008/jul/29/davidmiliband.labour |url-status=live |archivedate=31 July 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> The piece was widely interpreted as a leadership challenge to the then Prime Minister, not least because the timing of its publication \u2013 just after Brown's departure on holiday at the start of the parliamentary summer recess, and while there was intense speculation about his continuing leadership following Labour's defeat in the [[2008 Glasgow East by-election|Glasgow East by-election]] the previous week \u2013 seemed designed to produce a large political impact. In the following days two Labour MPs called on Brown to sack Miliband for his perceived disloyalty. Miliband, while denying claims by his detractors that he was seeking to provoke an early leadership election, did not rule himself out of eventually running for the leadership of the party. Many grassroots supporters believed a David Miliband-led Labour Party would tackle the Conservatives more effectively, reaching out to voters in marginal seats as well as securing Labour's core support.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2 August 2008 |date=31 July 2008 |agency=[[Reuters]] |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/Internal_ReutersCoUkService_14/idUKADD02799420080731 |title=Miliband calms leadership talk |archivedate=12 January 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090112003850/http://uk.reuters.com/article/Internal_ReutersCoUkService_14/idUKADD02799420080731 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=30 July 2008 |title=Miliband denies 'leadership' bid |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7532691.stm |publisher=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080731012407/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7532691.stm |archivedate=31 July 2008 |url-status=live |accessdate=2 August 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n====Campaign====\nThe Labour Party lost the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|UK general election]] held on 6 May 2010, and [[Gordon Brown]] soon announced that he was standing down as leader of the party.\n\nOn 12 May, flanked by 15 supportive members of the parliamentary party, Miliband announced from outside the House of Commons that he would stand in the resulting [[2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|leadership election]].<ref name=leaderguardian>{{cite news|author=Allegra Stratton |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/12/labourleadership-labour |title=David Miliband announces Labour leadership bid |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100513035441/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2010/may/12/labourleadership-labour |accessdate=7 June 2010 |location=London |archivedate=13 May 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> On 10 June 2010, [[Barry Sheerman]], Huddersfield MP, nominated Miliband for the Labour Party leadership post with Mr. Sheerman's daughter, Madlin Sadler, as Miliband's Campaign Co-ordinator. Madlin Sadler had served under Miliband previously as Special Advisor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/news/west-yorkshire-news/barry-sheerman-nominates-david-miliband-4996209|title=Barry Sheerman nominates David Miliband for Labour leader|newspaper=[[Huddersfield Daily Examiner]]|date=10 June 2010|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe other contenders for the leadership were [[Ed Balls]], [[Andy Burnham]], [[Diane Abbott]] and David's brother [[Ed Miliband]], with David Miliband gaining the most nominations. The result of the contest was announced on 25 September 2010, the day before the start of the 2010 [[Labour Party (UK) Conference|Labour Party Conference]] in Manchester. While David Miliband led the share of the electoral college votes in the first three rounds, he lost in the final round (50.65% to 49.35%) to his brother Ed. He announced on 29 September 2010 that he would be quitting frontline politics and would not be a part of his brother Ed's shadow cabinet.<ref>{{cite news|author=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Mulholland |date=29 September 2010 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/sep/29/david-miliband-quits-frontline-politics |title=David Miliband quits frontline politics |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2010/sep/29/david-miliband-quits-frontline-politics |url-status=live |archivedate=30 June 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Retirement from politics===\nMiliband resigned from the shadow cabinet in October 2010, but continued to serve as the MP for [[South Shields]]. He also taught A-Level Government and Politics on a voluntary basis at [[Haverstock School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/8253466/David-Miliband-to-become-a-teacher.html |location=London |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=11 January 2011 |first=Anita |last=Singh |title=David Miliband to become a teacher |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/8253466/David-Miliband-to-become-a-teacher.html |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2011, he became Senior Global Advisor for [[Oxford Analytica]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxan.com/about/ourpeople/senioradvisors/davidmiliband.aspx |title=Oxford Analytica \u2013 DavidMiliband |accessdate=26 March 2013 |publisher=[[Oxford Analytica|Oxan.com]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516210944/http://www.oxan.com/about/ourpeople/senioradvisors/davidmiliband.aspx |url-status=live |archivedate=16 May 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Leadership of the International Rescue Committee==\nOn 26 March 2013 the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' reported that Miliband would be announcing the following day that he intended to resign as an MP and leave politics altogether. He announced that he was taking up the post of head of the [[International Rescue Committee]] in New York, for which his remuneration would be \u00a3300,000 ($450,000) a year.<ref name=BBC21947497>{{cite news|date=26 March 2013 |accessdate=26 March 2013 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21947497 |title=David Miliband to step down as MP |publisher=[[BBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327013831/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21947497 |archivedate=27 March 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=27 March 2013 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/mar/27/david-miliband-diplomatic-test-irc |title=David Miliband faces a diplomatic test at the IRC |author=Robert Booth |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=28 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328101407/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2013/mar/27/david-miliband-diplomatic-test-irc |archivedate=28 March 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21950493 |title=David Miliband 'feared being distraction' for Labour |date=27 March 2013 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=28 March 2013 |archivedate=27 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327085006/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21950493 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nMiliband became the president and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of the [[International Rescue Committee]] on 1 September 2013. At the IRC, Miliband has been overseeing humanitarian aid and development programs in 40 countries, a global staff of 12,000 and 1,300 volunteers, and an annual budget of $450 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/david-miliband-former-uk-foreign-secretary-takes-helm-of-international-rescue-committee-222146991.html |title=David Miliband, Former UK Foreign Secretary, Takes Helm of International Rescue Committee |place=New York City |work=[[U.S. Newswire]] |agency=[[PR Newswire]] |date=3 September 2013 |accessdate=24 November 2013 |archivedate=2 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102044019/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/david-miliband-former-uk-foreign-secretary-takes-helm-of-international-rescue-committee-222146991.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> Near the top of the IRC, Miliband again installed his former Special Political Advisor from London, Madlin Sadler. She became the aid agency's Chief of Staff.<ref>{{cite web|title=IRC Leadership |accessdate=24 November 2013 |url=http://www.rescue.org/leadership |publisher=[[International Rescue Committee]] (IRC) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102203336/http://www.rescue.org/leadership |url-status=live |archivedate=2 November 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Syria's civil war===\nThe IRC has been responding to [[Refugees of the Syrian Civil War|Syria's refugee crisis]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=24 November 2013|url=http://www.rescue.org|title=Rescue and Refugee Support|publisher=Rescue.org}}</ref> On the [[ABC News]] programme of 13 October 2013, ''[[This Week (American TV program)|This Week]]'' with [[George Stephanopoulos]], Miliband commented that he worried about the immediate effects of the current diplomatic solution in Syria of sending in Chemical Weapons Inspectors and [[Destruction of Syria's chemical weapons|destroying the chemical stockpiles]] would have on the ongoing crisis. He said: \"We\u2019re concerned that people think that somehow, because the chemical weapons seem to be addressed, that the Syrian conflict, the regional conflict, is done and dusted.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|date=13 October 2013 |accessdate=24 November 2013 |last=Crowder |first=Anja |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2013/10/david-miliband-calls-nobel-peace-prize-award-a-bit-of-an-irony/ |title=David Miliband Calls Nobel Peace Prize Award 'A Bit of an Irony' |publisher=[[ABC News]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013210309/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2013/10/david-miliband-calls-nobel-peace-prize-award-a-bit-of-an-irony |archivedate=13 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> On 10 October 2013, he said there were huge risks in not intervening militarily. \"We've got people on the ground, not just in Syria but in Turkey, Lebanon, Jordan and Iraq,\u201d he told a foreign policy discussion in [[Manhattan]]. \u201cI\u2019ve got people who are in danger.\u201d He quoted [[Frederick the Great]], saying: \u201cDiplomacy without weapons is like music without instruments\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|date=10 October 2013 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10371282/David-Miliband-warns-of-huge-risks-of-Western-retreat-from-international-engagement.html |title=David Miliband warns of 'huge risks' of Western retreat from international engagement |accessdate=24 November 2013 |author=Jon Swaine |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url-status=live |archivedate=11 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011015710/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10371282/David-Miliband-warns-of-huge-risks-of-Western-retreat-from-international-engagement.html |df=dmy }}</ref> His policy opinions were at odds with his younger brother, [[Ed Miliband]], the Labour Party's Leader in the UK who insisted that the Labour Party would not back military intervention.<ref>{{cite news|last=Holehouse |first=Matthew |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10290476/Syria-crisis-Tony-Blair-criticises-Ed-Milibands-stance-on-military-action.html |title=Syria crisis: Tony Blair criticises Ed Miliband's stance on military action |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=6 September 2013 |accessdate=24 November 2013 |archivedate=9 September 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909050853/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10290476/Syria-crisis-Tony-Blair-criticises-Ed-Milibands-stance-on-military-action.html |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 2014, in a TV interview with ''[[KPBS (TV)|KPBS Evening Edition]]'' in [[San Diego]], Miliband reiterated that the US and other nations needed to intervene \"both politically as well as financially\" in Syria where one in two Syrians was displaced because the government of [[Bashar al-Assad]] was \"dropping [[barrel bombs]] on its own citizens\".<ref name=kpbs>{{cite news|author1=Megan Burke |author2=Peggy Pico |url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2014/feb/28/international-rescue-committees-david-miliband-wha/ |title=International Rescue Committee's David Miliband On What U.S. Can Do To Help Syrian Refugees |publisher=[[KPBS (TV)|KPBS]] |date=28 February 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403162901/http://www.kpbs.org/news/2014/feb/28/international-rescue-committees-david-miliband-wha/ |url-status=live |archivedate=3 April 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn [[KPBS (TV)|KPBS]], he revealed that the IRC was running cross-border aid to Syrians beyond the scope of the United Nations. Miliband said such \"cross border aid\" has reached about a half million Syrians with medical aid in cities that were \"besieged and cut off from the UN help\". Another half million Syrians, said Miliband, had received non-medical aid. Miliband stated that in the UN's absence, \"It comes to International NGOs, non governmental organisations, to get across the border crossings and weave their way between the conflict lines to reach people.\" He stated the need for such extraordinary efforts was great and the need for such ingenuity was even greater.<ref name=kpbs/>\n\n===Typhoon Haiyan===\nOn 10 November 2013, as IRC CEO, Miliband ordered the war relief agency to mount an emergency response to a natural disaster\u2014[[Typhoon Haiyan]] in the [[Philippines]]. He announced a huge donation drive for funds dedicated exclusively to the storm: \"In the face of a rising death toll and widespread humanitarian catastrophe the International Rescue Committee (IRC) has dispatched an emergency team to Manila and launched a $10 million appeal in order to implement the most appropriate response. We have today taken the decision to deploy emergency relief coordinators to the Philippines, with a view to deciding with the host government which of IRC's areas of expertise \u2014 from water and sanitation to education \u2014 are most needed. The IRC\u2019s emergency unit will start work immediately.\"<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.rescue-uk.org/node/1408 |title=International Rescue Committee deploys to Philippines in response to Typhoon Haiyan |publisher=International Rescue Committee UK (IRC-UK) |date=11 November 2013 |accessdate=24 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202225556/http://www.rescue-uk.org/node/1408 |archivedate=2 December 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nMiliband is co-chair of the [[Global Ocean Commission]] which was founded in February 2013.\n\nIn 2017, the organization provided 1.14 million children with schooling and education; helped resettle 10,665 refugees and special immigrant visa holders in the US; and filed 663 affidavit of relationships to help reunite families separated at the US border. In April 2018, Miliband told the New York Times that he joined the IRC with the idea that it \"should not be a sleeping giant, it should be a roused leader in the global humanitarian sector.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Brexit==\nIn May 2018, Miliband joined [[Nick Clegg]] and [[Nicky Morgan]] in calling for a [[Brexit|soft Brexit]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Culbertson | first = Alix |title=David Miliband joins Nick Clegg and Nicky Morgan in call for soft Brexit |url=https://news.sky.com/story/david-miliband-joins-nick-clegg-and-nicky-morgan-in-call-for-soft-brexit-11370115|work=Sky News|date=14 May 2018|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Expense claims==\n{{Main|United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal}}\n\nThe ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]'''s investigation of expenses claims by Members of Parliament reported that Miliband had claimed for gardening expenses and approximately \u00a330,000 in repairs, decorations and furnishings for his constituency home in [[South Shields]]. A spokesperson said: \"At every stage, David Miliband followed the procedures and rules as laid out by the parliamentary authorities\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Prince |first=Rosa |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293729/David-Miliband-challenged-by-gardener-MPs-expenses.html |title=Daily Telegraph: David Miliband |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=13 May 2009 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511064124/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293729/David-Miliband-challenged-by-gardener-MPs-expenses.html |archivedate=11 May 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Business interests==\nOn 21 December 2010, the Office of David Miliband Limited was formed with Miliband and his wife Louise as directors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk/30a0a493168a75322381e16a115f7cdf/compdetails/|title=Companies House website}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', \"much of Mr Miliband\u2019s time has been spent on his lucrative directorships and speaking roles, which he would be expected to give up if he returned to frontline politics\u2026as of January 2013, David Miliband has made just short of \u00a31m on top of his MP\u2019s salary since he failed to win the Labour leadership in the summer of 2010.\"<ref name=\"ft.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f4eb64dc-5fdb-11e2-8d8d-00144feab49a.html |last=Pickard |first=Jim |title=Spotlight cast on David Miliband earnings |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=18 January 2013 |accessdate=24 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130122165452/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f4eb64dc-5fdb-11e2-8d8d-00144feab49a.html#axzz2l1Zujq5u |archivedate=22 January 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a March 2013 article in the ''[[HuffPost|Huffington Post UK]]'', Miliband has earned almost \u00a31m since the 2010 election. The article listed sources of income from speaking (where he has earned up to \u00a320,000 per event), advisory and teaching roles, journalism, gifts, hospitality and overseas visits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/03/27/david-miliband-resigns-salary-charity_n_2962227.html |title=David Miliband 'Could Earn Hundreds Of Thousands Of Dollars' At International Rescue Committee|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=24 November 2013|date=27 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nMiliband is one of six members of the Global Advisory Board of Macro Advisory Partners, which advises multinational corporations, sovereign wealth funds, investors and governments.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=24 November 2013 |url=http://www.macroadvisorypartners.com/the-firm/global-advisory-board |title=Global Advisory Board |publisher=Macro Advisory Partners |archivedate=2 November 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102142646/http://www.macroadvisorypartners.com/the-firm/global-advisory-board |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, David Miliband joined the Board of Directors of [[Mauritius]]-based private equity group, Indus Basin Holdings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indusbasin.com/profile.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203150732/http://www.indusbasin.com/profile.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 December 2013|title=Profile|quote=Indus Basin Holding Ltd is incorporated in Mauritius, and licensed by the Mauritius Financial Services Commission|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref> IBH operates Rice Partners <ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Indus Basin Holdings]] |accessdate=24 November 2013 |url=http://www.indusbasin.com/businesses.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223708/http://www.indusbasin.com/businesses.html |url-status=live |archivedate=2 December 2013 |title=Indus Basin Holdings \u2013 Businesses |df=dmy }}</ref> in the [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] region of Pakistan which specialises in managing the end-to-end supply chain for major global users of rice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tirmizi |first=Farooq |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/281091/cutting-out-the-middleman-global-food-giant-to-buy-pakistani-rice-directly-from-the-paddy/ |title=Cutting out the middleman: Global food giant to buy Pakistani rice directly from the paddy |newspaper=[[The Express Tribune]] (Pakistan) |date=25 October 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025121845/http://tribune.com.pk/story/281091/cutting-out-the-middleman-global-food-giant-to-buy-pakistani-rice-directly-from-the-paddy/ |url-status=live |archivedate=25 October 2011 |accessdate=24 November 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Tirmizi |first=Farooq |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/324941/high-connections-david-miliband-joins-pakistani-private-equity-firm/ |title=High connections: David Miliband joins Pakistani private equity firm |newspaper=[[The Express Tribune]] |date=21 January 2012 |accessdate=24 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203002745/http://tribune.com.pk/story/324941/high-connections-david-miliband-joins-pakistani-private-equity-firm/ |archivedate=3 December 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Financial Times]]'',<ref name=\"ft.com\"/> \"Mr Miliband\u2019s jobs include advisory roles with [[VantagePoint Capital Partners]], a Californian group; [[Oxford Analytica]], a UK advisory company; and Indus Basin Holdings, a Pakistani agrochemical group. He is also a member of the advisory board to the [[Sir Bani Yas]] academic forum, which is hosted by the [[Foreign relations of the United Arab Emirates|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the United Arab Emirates]]. Despite supporting [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], Mr Miliband is vice-chairman and a non-executive director of [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. As a speaker he commands a fee of up to \u00a320,000.\"\n\nMiliband is also on the Advisory Board of VantagePoint Capital Partners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vpcp.com/advisory_council |title=Advisory Council &#124; |publisher=[[VantagePoint Capital Partners]] |accessdate=24 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513054854/http://www.vpcp.com/advisory_council |archivedate=13 May 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nMiliband is a member of the [[Trilateral Commission]], founded and chaired by [[David Rockefeller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trilateral.org/download/file/TC_list_1-13(1).pdf|title=THE TRILATERAL COMMISSION JANUARY 2013|publisher=The Trilateral Commission|accessdate=23 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220012940/http://www.trilateral.org/download/file/TC_list_1-13%281%29.pdf|archivedate=20 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}\"David Miliband, Member of the British Parliament; former Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, London\"</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMiliband married Louise Shackelton, a professional violinist formerly with the [[London Symphony Orchestra]], in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wheeler |first=Brian |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11409402 |title=The David Miliband Story |publisher=BBC News |date=29 September 2010 |accessdate=29 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522151656/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11409402 |archivedate=22 May 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Miliband makes his mark|date=3 February 2006|author=Vivienne Russell|url=http://www.publicfinance.co.uk/features/2006/miliband-makes-his-mark-by-vivienne-russell/|publisher=PublicFinance}}</ref> Shackelton and Miliband have adopted two newborn sons from the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidmiliband.net/about-david-2/davids-story/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305220212/http://www.davidmiliband.net/about-david-2/davids-story/ |archivedate=5 March 2011 |title=David's Story |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> the first in December 2004 and the second in October 2007,<ref>{{cite news|date=31 December 2004|author=Andrew Norfolk|title=Blair's lieutenant adopts American baby|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article407171.ece|accessdate=15 May 2007|newspaper=[[The Times]]|location=London|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=29 October 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7067282.stm |title=David Miliband adopts second son |accessdate=29 October 2007 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7067282.stm |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=David Miliband speaks of adopting his sons |last=Clout |first=Laura |location=London |date=13 June 2008 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/2120096/David-Miliband-speaks-of-adopting-his-sons.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=11 May 2010 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/2120096/David-Miliband-speaks-of-adopting-his-sons.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\nand currently live in New York City's Upper West Side.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/08/fashion/Former-British-Foreign-Secretary-david-milibands-new-york-life.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=6 December 2013 |title=An Englishman in New York |author=Sarah Lyalll |accessdate=21 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831233734/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/08/fashion/Former-British-Foreign-Secretary-david-milibands-new-york-life.html?_r=1& |archivedate=31 August 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\nIn an interview with [[CNN]] in 2009, Miliband stated that he grew up in a secular setting and describes himself as an [[Atheism|atheist]] with a \"huge respect\" for people of faith.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|title=Interview With David Miliband |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=5 July 2009 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0907/05/fzgps.01.html |accessdate=24 January 2010 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0907/05/fzgps.01.html |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nMiliband was portrayed by [[Henry Lloyd-Hughes]] in the [[Docudrama|docu-drama]] ''[[Miliband of Brothers]]'', with [[Ed Miliband]] being portrayed by Lloyd Hughes' brother [[Ben Lloyd-Hughes]].\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*2016 Honorary Doctorate, [[The New School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newschool.edu/pressroom/pressreleases/2016/commencement2016.htm |title=LAVERNE COX, DIANE VON FURSTENBERG, DERAY MCKESSON NAMED HONORARY DEGREE RECIPIENTS BY THE NEW SCHOOL |date=2016-03-31 }}</ref>\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|ref={{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1=1.'''David Miliband'''\n|2=2. [[Ralph Miliband]]\n|3=3. [[Marion Kozak]]\n|4=4. Samuel Miliband\n|5=5. Renia Steinlauf\n|6